However, we must consider the case when n is 1: the loop is not executed, so we only output:

        "1 "

      and then nothing else. This matches the second program. But note: the second program in Java does:

        System.out.println(n + " ");
        for (int i = n - 1; i > 0; i--) { if (m % i == 0) {
                System.out.println(i + " ");
                m = i;
            }
        }

      So we are mimicking that. One more thing: what if the first program's output is zero? Then n=0. Then the loop: i from -1 down to 1 -> no iteration. So output is "0 " and then nothing. This is acceptable. Therefore, the Fortran code: We assume the string is read as a token (without spaces). We use read(*,*) S.

  However, what if the string has spaces? The first Java program uses next() which reads one token. So we must read one token.
